  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 동명(東明) : '
    value: 고구려  시조(始祖). 그러나 여기 읊어진 이는 그 아버지, 북부여왕(北夫餘王) 해모수(解慕漱).
  - key: '[주-D002] 화성(化城)이 치솟았네 : '
    value: 법화도사(法華道師)가 험한 길 가운데서 변화(變化)를 부려 한 성(城)을 만들어 피로한 대중(大衆)들을 그 안에 들어가서 쉬게 하였다. 《法華經》
  - key: '[주-D003] 곰소[熊淵] : '
    value: 해모수(解慕漱)가 청하(靑河 鳴錄江) 하백(河伯)의 맏딸 유화(柳花)를 만났다는 곳.
  - key: '[주-D004] 조천대(朝天臺) : '
    value: 부벽루 아래 있는 기린굴(麒麟窟) 남쪽에 있는데, 세상에서 전하되 동명왕이 기린말을 타고 이 굴에 들어갔다가 땅속에서 조천석이 되어 솟아나와 하늘로 올라갔다 하며, 그 말발굽 자국이 돌 위에 있다고 한다. 《輿覽》평양의 동명왕 관계 고적은 모두 와전(訛傳)이며, 동명왕이 평양에 도읍한 일도 없다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 용언궐(龍堰闕) : '
    value: 고구려 때 궁궐. 《三國遺事》
  - key: '[주-D006] 구제궁(九梯宮) : '
    value: 영명사(永明寺) 안에 있는데 동명왕의 궁이라 하나(《輿覽》) 고구려 시대 이궁(離宮)인 것 같다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 유람할 곳은 …… 청원루(淸遠樓) : '
    value: 다경루, 청원루는 모두 평양부 서쪽 9리 양명포(揚命浦) 위에 있는데, 대안(對岸)에 돌을 쌓고 그 위에 다락을 지었는데, 그 밑으로 통할 만하다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 미꾸라지 …… 상어 : '
    value: 열거한 고기 이름이 담수어(淡水魚) 아닌 바닷고기들이 되는 대로 섞였음은 부가(富家)의 과식(誇飾)이다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 이 사이에 …… 없어졌다. : '
    value: 서경의 단(段)이 끝난 뒤 대부(大夫)의 평이 있었겠고, 다음 북경(北京 송도)에 관한 대부의 물음에 대한 담수(談叟)의 대답 중 앞의 부분이 궐했은즉, 아마 몇백 자, 몇십 귀가 빠진 듯하다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 곡령(鵠嶺) …… 누르다 : '
    value: 최치원이 신라가 망하고 고려가 흥할 것을 알고, 고려  태조에게, “곡령에 솔이 푸르고 계림엔 잎이 누르다.[鵠嶺靑松鷄林黃葉]”란 글을 올렸다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 앞에는 …… 오리 : '
    value: 당나라 상인 왕창근(王昌瑾)이 이인(異人)에게 샀노라 하여 궁예(宮裔)에게 바친 옛 거울에 새긴 문구 중의 일절, “선조계 후박압(先操鷄 後搏鴨).” 이것을 왕건(王建)이, “먼저 계림(신라)를 멸하고 뒤에 압록강을 취한다.”는 뜻으로 당시 해석했다.
  - key: '[주-D012] 안산(案山)ㆍ화형(花形) : '
    value: 안산(案山)은 풍수가들이 말하는 터나 묘(墓)의 앞산. 화형(花形)은 풍수설에서 산수(山水)의 발맥(發脈).
  - key: '[주-D013] 각(角) …… 주먹처럼 : '
    value: 각(角)과 상(商)은 다 오음(五音) 중의 명칭이나 방위(方位)로도 논하는데, 산세(山勢)의 길형(吉形)을 말하는 풍수가들의 용어.
  - key: '[주-D014] 뽕나무 뿌리에 맨 : '
    value: “망하지 않을까 망하지 않을까 하고 경계해, 뽕나무 우거진 뿌리에 매어 둔 것처럼 견고해진다.[其亡其亡 繫于苞桑]”《周易否》망할 듯하다가 다시 유지된다는 뜻이다.
  - key: '[주-D015] 한 자[尺] …… 아니라 : '
    value: “한 자 구슬이 귀하지 않고, 촌음이 중하다.”는 옛말이 있다.
  - key: '[주-D016] 조충(雕蟲)의 작은 재주 : '
    value: 조충전각(彫蟲篆刻), 조충소기(彫虫小技)니 하는 말이 있는데, 이것은 시문(詩文)ㆍ사부(詞賦) 등의 문예(文藝)를 도덕이나 사업에 비하면 조충의 조그만 기교(技巧)란 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D017] 샘물ㆍ등불 …… 않거든 : '
    value: 남북조(南北朝) 시대에 양(梁)나라 하원(何遠)이 무창태수(武昌太守)가 되었는데, 여름에 마실 물이 나쁘므로 사람을 시켜 민가(民家)의 좋은 우물의 냉수(冷水)를 길어다 먹으면서 물값으로 돈을 주었는데 주인이 받지 아니하니, “그러면 그 물은 길어다 먹지 않겠다.” 하며 기어이 돈을 주었다.
  - key: '[주-D018] 밥상엔 생선 없이 : '
    value: 맹상군(孟常君)의 식객(食客) 풍환(馮驩)이 노래하기를, “밥에 생선이 없네.[食無魚]”라 했다. 《史記》실세(失勢)를 말한다.
  - key: '[주-D019] 《주역》의 수괘(需卦) : '
    value: 음식의 풍부함을 말한 것이 많다.
  - key: '[주-D020] 《시경》의 기취(旣醉) : '
    value: 귀족들의 태평 주연(酒宴)의 노래인데, 이 노래에, “술이 이미 취했는데, 또 덕으로 배불리네.[飮醉以酒 叉飽以德]”라는 구절이 있다.
  - key: '[주-D021] 금오(金鼇)가 …… 치받쳤다 : '
    value: 발해(渤海) 동쪽에 큰 구멍이 있고 가운데 다섯 산이 있었는데, 부리가 연착(連着)되지 않아 늘 물결을 따라 아래위로 흔들리니, 상제(上帝)가 노하여 서극으로 귀양 보내니 뭇 성인들이 살 곳을 잃었다. 이에 큰 자라 열다섯 마리에게 시켜 머리를 들어 이게 하였다한다. 성인들이 살 만한 산을 말한다.
  - key: '[주-D022] 나라를 …… 않도다 : '
    value: 나라의 견고함이 산하(山河)의 미(美)와 성지(城池)의 험함에 있지 않고, 임금이 백성에게 덕으로 다스림에 있다는 말. 전국 때 위무후(魏武侯)가 서하에 배를 띄워 내려가면서 오기(吳起)를 돌아보며 말하되, “아름답다, 산하(山河)의 굳음이여, 이는 위나라의 보배로다.” 하니 오기가 말하되, “덕이 있고, 험함에 있지 않으니이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D023] 거교(鉅橋) : '
    value: 은주(殷紂)의 큰 곡식 창고가 있던 땅. 주 무왕(周武王)이 주(紂)를 치고 거교의 조[粟]을 꺼내어 은(殷)나라의 주린 백성들을 진휼했다. 《史記》
  - key: '[주-D024] 용과 …… 이어가고 : '
    value: 용상(龍象)은 고승(高僧)을, 사자후(獅子吼)는 설법(說法)을 말하며, 천의 등불이 이어짐은 전도(傳道)를 말한다.
  - key: '[주-D025] 진(秦)나라를 거울 삼아 : '
    value: 진 시황(秦始皇)이 아방궁(阿房宮) 같은 큰 궁궐을 지어 백성을 괴롭혔으므로 민심을 잃어 궁도 불타고 나라가 망했다.
  - key: '[주-D026] 작은 나라로 …… 보전하니 : '
    value: 대국(大國)이 소국(小國)을 섬기는 것은 낙천(樂天)하는 것이요, 소국이 대국을 섬기는 것은 하늘의 위엄을 두려워하는 것이다. 《孟子》
  - key: '[주-D027] 문(文)과 …… 달랐으나 : '
    value: 하(夏)나라는 충(忠)을 숭상하였고, 은(殷)나라는 질(質)을 숭상하고, 주(周)나라는 문(文)을 숭상하였다.
  - key: '[주-D001] 壞 : '
    value: 壤
english:
  title: The Western Capital
  author: Choe Ja
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A silver-tongued youth from the Western Capital met an old storyteller from the Northern Capital, and together they came to wander Kangdo. There they encountered a Minister of Rectitude who said, "I have heard the names of two great capitals, yet never beheld their glory. Fortune brings you both before me—pray, let an old man's curiosity be satisfied. Tell me of these two cities."

    The youth began: "When the Western Capital was first established, the Divine King came down from the Nine Heavens and chose this earth as his dwelling. Without foundation laid or walls constructed, a transforming city rose like a vision. In a five-dragon carriage he ascended and descended through heaven, guided by a hundred celestial spirits, followed by ranks of immortals. At Bear's Pool he met the heavenly maiden, their encounters fluttering like butterflies. In the river stands a stone called the Terrace of Heaven-Worship—now seeming a flat rock, now soaring as a cliff. When the King ascended there, divine chariots lingered in his wake. Where spirits dwell, earthly shrines crumble. He summoned the Wind Count and commanded the Rain Master. In his anger, hail fell at noon and thunder split the heavens, trees and stones flying together. There is also the spirit of Mount Mok, keeper of harvests: without plowing, grain ripens abundantly, stacked like mountains, sheltering both lord and commoner beneath its bounty."

    The Minister replied, "Such divine wonders seem mere fanciful tales. How can they serve as boasts?"

    The youth continued: "As for magnificent sights—there are the Dragon-Dam Palaces with nine-tiered halls, vast and open, bright and soaring, folding the cosmos within them, confusing east and west. Heaven cannot diminish their majesty, demons cannot contest their achievement. The places of wandering and viewing—landscapes spanning the azure sea, vistas stretching across half the sky, emerald waters facing boundless depths, the Hall of Eternal Light arching overhead. Where countless waters converge bears the name Great Harmony. Shimmering and rippling, embracing fertile lands and drawing in distant rivers, it spreads like white silk, clear as bronze mirrors. On both banks, drooping willows dance all day in wind. Across level sand and open fields, migrating geese cry and wild ducks call. Green mountains encircle the walls on four sides, towering and steep. In the gentle rain, a fisherman in straw cape appears below. At dusk, a shepherd boy's distant flute is heard. Pictures cannot capture it, verses cannot exhaust it. When we release silk moorings and set the orchid boat adrift, turning mid-stream to look back, we seem suspended in mirror and screen. Thus our capital's natural advantages are indeed supreme under heaven."

    The Minister said, "Such exotic marvels dazzle and enchant the heart."

    The youth replied: "Where fish are caught, a long net yields abundance—obscure mud-fish, great sturgeon, mullet and pike, flying fish and countless others of humble taste. Yet when winter freezes the entire river, the silken-scaled fish below shimmer like pearls. With iron spear and fork, a hundred are caught without one escaping. Placed on platters overnight, they freeze crystalline as jade. The kitchen master, wielding his blade with skill, cuts gossamer slices—streaks of silver, color supreme, flavor supreme. A single taste chills the teeth and freezes the throat like hoarfrost and snow."

    Here a passage of the text is missing, yet what follows remains true as an ancient seal.

    The youth continued: "There once lived Choe the Solitary Recluse who said, 'The breath of sages ferments in the northern mountains: at Crane-Peak the pines stay green, at Chicken-Realm the leaves turn yellow. Before purple clouds rise, fate is foretold—the iron mirror fell from heaven predicting: first the fowl, then the duck, confirming this prophecy.' When the three lands unified and the bright hall was established, North Peak reclines like cattle, South Mountain soars like dragon-flight. Right embraces, left holds, the Case-Mountain and Flower-Form align. Eight heads and three tails span east ridge and western hill. In hidden, coiled movement, limbs and joints bend and clasp. Ascending essence summons descending spirit, exhaled breath produces auspicious signs. The five rivers' sacred currents flow from distant depths. Ten thousand streams gather and surge forth. Swift as arrows, swift as wheels, they rush toward the center, bringing together spirit and virtue to nourish all prosperity. The green pine flourishes—three hundred seasons pass. Declining, then flourishing again, it holds to the mulberry root, steadfast. Since ancient times like us, answering prophecy in founding the realm—how many kings have ruled?"

    The Minister said, "The sage-ancestor's dragon-throne responds to Heaven's mandate and the people's heart, not by geography's wild theories."

    The old man of the North said: "In the Central Plain, iron is produced—refined metal, lead, steel, soft iron. From mountain-stone flows what no hammer can extract. Quarrying root and stump without limit, the great furnace glows, molten streams rage with flame. Tempered by sunlight's pattern, quenched in water's darkness, the old smith's hammer—a hundred strikes, a thousand forgings—creates spear-points and arrowheads, lances and coats, swords and spears, cauldrons and vessels, hoes and tools, pots and pans. For household use these suffice; for war's defense these serve. In Chicken-Realm forever and Northern-Stronghold, mulberry trees flourish. Each spring brings silkworms—one household keeps ten thousand frames. Each summer yields thread—one finger draws a hundred spools. First the silk unravels and tangles together; now the loom weaves with fine threads. Thunder-sound of shuttles, wind-sound of bobbins—beneath the hands comes lightning-flash. Damasks and gauzes, silks and muslins, silks thin as mist and gauze, snowy white and frost-pale, dyed blue and yellow, red and green become brocades and embroidered silks. Nobles wear them, women dress in them. Trailing sounds and rustling shine—this is Heaven's storehouse, nation's treasures scattered everywhere."

    The Minister replied, "A foot of pearl is hardly treasure—what then of metals and silk?"

    The old man continued: "Poets and painters throng here shoulder to shoulder: crimson feelings and green thoughts, embroidered mouths and brocaded hearts. They chew ice and gnaw snow, carving jade and chiseling gold. When the brush flies, thunder and lightning seem less swift; when poems multiply, clear rivers and sheer cliffs cannot match their depth. Worn phrases are not recycled from ancient times; new expressions spring forth, novel in this age. The warriors and fierce soldiers—in short-cut robes with dangling cordons, bearing serpent-swords and grasping dragon-blades, leaping and striking, roaring and bellowing, seizing like bears, raking like tigers, pouncing like hawks, bounding like apes, glaring with anger, flinging arms with lightness. One arrow-shot strikes three targets; one lance-play loops the ball a hundred times. Are these not the nation's treasures?"

    The Minister objected: "Such carved insects and violent strength the superior man disdains, much less ball-juggling tricks."

    The old man said: "Officials are appointed, duties assigned—thousands within, ten-thousands without. Murky is clarified, clear is elevated, talent raised without confusion. Each spring the Spring Minister selects the virtuous and worthy. Purple sashes and official rank fill the court, courtiers brandish their symbols. Going out as censors or governing provinces, all take ice-clarity and jade-purity as their duty, neither stealing water-lamp benefits nor accepting bundled bribes. Tearing threads for lampwicks, casting coins for drink—doors stand vacant, tables lack fish, chill and simplicity prevail. All admire their names, they boast of untainted honor. Yet to awe the people, they deem cruelty necessary, examining trifles and exposing hidden shadows, scraping and seeking until no blemish escapes. Then shackles bind and ropes mark; beating yields not to a hundred strokes, strangling requires doubled cord. Officials lose their limbs, people lose their courage. Whispers and trembling, fear and dread—speak one word and disputes vanish, scold once and villains confess. Raising levies seems no burden, offering gifts seems no flattery. Urgent demands for taxes and tributes, transporting by water and land like fire and lightning—filling the national treasury and state granaries. The zealous service to state and nation cannot be fully told."

    The Minister said: "False piety and cruel harshness are worms eating the people—the harm is grave."

    The old man continued: "Ministers' mansions stretch for ten miles—towering pavilions with phoenixes dancing, cool halls and warm chambers arranged like scales. Gold and jade shine, vermillion and green gleam, silk adorns the pillars, patterned carpets spread the floors. Exotic trees and rare flowers, famous blooms and fragrant petals display spring's glory and summer's fruit, verdant groves and crimson clusters spreading fragrance, competing in charm. The inner quarters hold beauties in cloud-robes and mist-capes, every gesture, every allure arranged and attending. Lacquered tables and patterned seats, pipes and percussion, nine vessels of wine flow like waves, thousand goblets stand like mountains. Like the Hexagram of Need from the Book of Changes, like the satisfied drunkenness of the Ode—camel's hump and bear's paw, dragon's liver and phoenix marrow, bejeweled pyramids, treasures of jade—all heaped until spit out and discarded. Even merchants and commoners, even Buddhist monks enjoy grand houses and varied fare, exhausting pleasures of eye and ear, boasting exotic dress. Even lowly slaves dare imitate their betters, donning grand caps and official belts, adorning their belts and embellishing their shoes, wearing fine silks and close-woven gauze, competing in extravagant display. Even the splendor of Chang'an and Luoyang cannot compare."

    The Minister sighed: "Ah, the fall of the old Western Capital—was it not because of this?"

    Then the two western and northern guests bristled and flushed, speaking in mingled anger and shame: "All day we have spoken, yet the Minister refutes us all. We wish to hear of Kangdo."

    The Minister said: "Have you not heard something of Kangdo's nature? Let me briefly present one thread for discussion. The Eastern Sea is vast, containing nine rivers and eight streams, swallowing them like mustard seeds, drowning clouds and scorching suns, surging and billowing. Within lies Flower Mountain, where Golden Turtle stands high-backed. At the banks and islets cluster branches—where such branches gather scattered like chess-pieces are the dwellings of river-merchants, sea-traders, fishermen, salt-makers. Where stamens and calyxes arch in sacred peaks and spiritual hills, soaring like flying birds, stand imperial halls, heavenly palaces, mansions of ministers and people. Within lies the dense coil of Mauli-cave's mouth; without, the four barriers of Dongchin and White-Horse mountains. For entrance, the Eastern Gate of Emblem-Flower checks passage; for receiving guests, the Northern Harbor-Pavilion handles greeting. Twin peaks serve as thresholds, twin mountains as hinges—truly Heaven's secret precinct. Thus within it is girt with purple ramparts, without wrapped in white walls. Waters aid the encircling, mountains contend in height. Looking down, one shivers in abyssal depths; looking up, one grows dizzy at sheer cliffs. Ducks and geese cannot fly through, wolves and tigers cannot peek inside. One man bars the gate, ten thousand households sleep in peace. This is the city of bronze and steel, the eternal capital of sage-kings."

    The two guests said: "A nation's strength lies not in mountains and rivers, but in virtue, not in danger."

    The Minister replied: "The city itself is a harbor; outside the gates float boats. Whether gathering firewood or bearing grass, even a single leaf bears its freight. Land travel is swifter, gathering and transport easier. The kitchen never lacks fuel, the stable never lacks fodder. People rest, strength suffices, small effort yields great profit. Merchant vessels and tribute ships connect ten thousand miles of sail—heavy boats sail north, light sails drift south, oars end to stem, prows locked together. In one wind's moment the eight directions meet. Mountain delicacies and ocean treasures—nothing goes unshipped. Pounding jade and crushing pearls, ten-thousand-stone piles rise towering. Wrapped treasures and furred goods gathered from eight quarters heap and cluster. Competing boats arrive and anchor, suddenly streets fill and alleys narrow. Yet shifting these proves easy—why burden ourselves with carrying? By hand and shoulder, step after step, goods pile in government offices, overflow in private homes. Not like mountains yet towering, like springs yet widespread. Grain stores rot upon rot—can it match great Han's abundance?"

    The guests said: "Ultimate wealth comes not from hoarding—look to the Great Bridge as mirror."

    The Minister replied: "Buddhism flows from the Eastern Sea long ago; today faith grows ever deeper. For images and statues, we cast metal and mold clay, chisel stone and carve wood, sometimes embroider with threads or paint with brush, dignified in presence, serene as if alive. For scriptures and teachings, we have sutras, precepts, commentaries, meditation texts and patriarch-sayings, block-printed or brush-written, on gold and blood, yellow scrolls with red bindings, in pearl cases and silk wrappings—thousands upon thousands heaped in disorder. Meditation halls and teaching temples, public monasteries and private shrines, gatherings and hermitages, halls and rooms rise—who knows how many thousands? The fragrance of incense drifts ten thousand miles, the sound of bells and gongs echoes in four directions. Here long-eyebrowed monks in jade robes, green-eyed masters in gold garments, southern forests and northern groves, bamboo and reeds in rows like soldiers, dragons and elephants compete in their pawing, golden lions contend in roaring. Thousand lights of mind transmit flame through heart, countless seas of mouth surge forth in waves of sound. Morning burns incense to pray for the sovereign, evening lights candles to quell disaster. Yet deeming it insufficient, they built a special hermitage within the capital, inviting monks from beyond the world. Fleeing blue mountains and white clouds, entering purple roads and red dust, through staff and shout they summon wind and thunder, through the shout and shout they scatter rain and hail, executing and preserving freely, cutting at every point. Years ago during great calamity, sovereign and ministers redoubled their vow. Gathering all schools, chanting sutras each alternate day—the sounds of Buddha-calling and god-singing so urgent the mountains shake, the smoke of burning heads and seared fingers so thick the sun and moon lose light. Such extreme devotion and suffering! Surely the protective response and divine care must be limitless."

    The guests said: "Throughout history, no one revered Buddha like the Liang—yet why did it fall so swiftly?"

    The Minister replied: "Today our Sovereign practices frugality and favors his subjects."

    The two guests, startled and losing composure, rose to kneel, saying: "Minister, speak no more. This single statement suffices to reveal the perfection of perfect peace. When governance is clear and impartial, all begins with frugality. With frugality, customs return to integrity. How then would Heaven not favor us? How would our dynasty not endure long? What we spoke all day was mere empty chatter, only exposing the nation's old shame."

    The Minister said: "Hear me. I take ancient times as mirror. The Zhou were loyal and generous, enjoying eight hundred years. Emperor Wen of Han wore coarse cloth and leather shoes; his ministers were mostly generous and magnanimous elders, and the succession was limitless. Tang's Emperor Taizong honored frugality—wishing to build a single palace, he stopped upon reflecting on the Qin, and thus Fang Xuanling and Wei Zheng did not rest in security, maintaining the dynasty for three hundred years. Glorious is our realm—virtue exceeds antiquity, fearing Heaven's majesty, delighting in Heaven's way, the smaller serving the greater maintains preservation, neither plague nor pestilence afflicts the people, all dwell in peaceful brightness. Yet praise falls short; let me extend this meaning in song:

    From distant Yao and Shun down to Song and Tang,
    Though forms of culture shift, none escape fate's law:
    By extravagance they fall, by frugality they rise.
    West the willows collapsed through lust and were renamed the Willow Capital,
    North the pines drifted through excess and dispersed.
    Yet brilliant Kangdo stands solely on virtue's foundation,
    Following Heaven and serving the great, customs pure and harmonious.
    For ten thousand ages may we remain in peace,
    Never forgetting danger midst our prosperity.
